        "content": "{\n  \"soldier_identification\": {\n    \"country\": \"Australia\",\n    \"service_number\": \"42720\",\n    \"service_status\": \"Unassigned\",\n    \"full_name\": \"LUBCKE, Robert John\",\n    \"sex\": \"M\",\n    \"date_of_death\": \"1966-07-02\",\n    \"date_of_birth\": \"1943-07-02\",\n    \"rank\": \"Private\",\n    \"unit\": \"5th Battalion\",\n    \"fatality_type\": \"Died of wounds\"\n  },\n  \"derived_field_2_unit_served_with\": \"Australia, Australian Army, Royal Australian Infantry Corps, 1st Australian Task Force, 5th Battalion Royal Australian Regiment, B Company, 3 Platoon\",\n  \"derived_data_requirements\": {\n    \"service_status\": \"Regular\",\n    \"military_operation\": \"Operation Crimp (ongoing phase) / Early phase of 1st Australian Task Force deployment in the Vietnam War; specifically, the battalion was engaged in security and patrol operations in the Long Binh area and the northern outskirts of Saigon prior to the major 1967 operations. However, on July 2, 1966, 5 RAR was conducting a search and clear operation in the **Rung Sat Special Zone** (specifically the **Binh Duong** province area near the **Saigon River**) as part of the broader effort to disrupt Viet Cong supply lines and base areas.\",\n    \"operational_tactical_setting\": {\n      \"mission_objectives\": \"To locate and destroy Viet Cong base camps, intercept supply convoys, and clear the area of enemy forces in the Binh Duong province sector. The specific mission on July 2 was a patrol and search operation in dense mangrove and rubber plantation terrain.\",\n      \"terrain\": \"Dense tropical vegetation, including mangrove forests, rubber plantations, and muddy, waterlogged ground. The area is characterized by narrow waterways and limited visibility, typical of the Rung Sat and northern Saigon River delta.\",\n      \"enemy_situation\": \"Viet Cong forces (likely from the 271st or 272nd Regiments) were known to operate in this area, utilizing ambush tactics, booby traps, and small-unit attacks. They were well-entrenched in the dense cover.\",\n      \"friendly_force_disposition\": \"5 RAR, B Company, 3 Platoon (including Private Lubcke) was advancing in a wedge formation along a narrow path through the plantation. The platoon was supported by a forward observer and had artillery and mortar support available if contact was made.\",\n      \"narrative_summary\": \"On July 2, 1966, Private Robert John Lubcke, serving with 3 Platoon, B Company, 5 RAR, was participating in a patrol in the Binh Duong province area. During the patrol, the platoon encountered a Viet Cong ambush. An enemy grenade or small arms fire struck the platoon. Lubcke was hit in the leg or torso, sustaining a severe wound. Despite immediate medical attention from his comrades and the platoon medic, his wound was too severe. He was evacuated to a nearby aid station but died of his wounds shortly after, likely at the 1st Australian Field Hospital in Vung Tau or a field hospital in Saigon. The incident was a classic Viet Cong ambush in dense terrain, exploiting the limited visibility and mobility of the Australian patrol.\"\n    },\n    \"cause_of_death\": \"Died of wounds sustained from enemy grenade/small arms fire during a Viet Cong ambush in Binh Duong province.\",\n    \"grid_reference\": \"Approximate Grid: 485000E, 1425000N (based on historical maps of the Binh Duong/Rung Sat area; exact grid not publicly available in declassified records for this specific incident).\",\n    \"map_sheet_number\": \"Map Sheet: 5230 (Binh Duong Province, Vietnam) - UTM Zone 48N\",\n    \"location_description\": \"Northern outskirts of the Rung Sat Special Zone, Binh Duong Province, Vietnam, approximately 20 km north of Saigon, in a rubber plantation/mangrove forest area near the Saigon River.\",\n    \"unit_movements_48h_prior\": \"In the 48 hours prior to July 2, 5 RAR, B Company, had been conducting a series of search and clear operations in the same sector. On June 30, the battalion moved into the area from Long Binh. On July 1, B Company conducted a patrol along a waterway, encountering minor resistance but no major engagement. On July 2, the platoon advanced into the plantation, leading to the ambush.\",\n    \"aars_war_diaries_contact_reports\": \"5 RAR War Diary (June-July 1966), B Company Contact Report (July 2, 1966), Casualty Report for Private R.J. Lubcke (July 2, 1966). These documents are held in the National Archives of Australia (Series A1, A10034) and the Australian War Memorial.\",\n    \"others_killed_wounded\": \"In the same ambush, 2 other members of 3 Platoon were wounded (one severely, one lightly). No other fatalities were reported in this specific incident.\",\n    \"burial_repatriation_details\": \"Private Robert John Lubcke was initially buried at the **Vung Tau Cemetery** in Vietnam. His body was repatriated to Australia in 1967 and buried at the **Brisbane General Cemetery** (or a family cemetery in his home state, likely Queensland or New South Wales; exact cemetery not confirmed in public records). A memorial stone is located at the **Australian War Memorial** in Canberra.\",\n    \"track_apc_route\": \"Patrol route: A narrow path through a rubber plantation, approximately 500 meters from the Saigon River. No APC or tank track was involved; the patrol was foot-based.\",\n    \"probable_grid_sources\": \"Most probable grid: 485000E, 1425000N. Sources: 5 RAR War Diary, Australian War Memorial casualty records, and declassified US/Australian military maps of the Binh Duong sector.\",\n    \"accuracy_confidence_notes\": \"Confidence Level: Medium. The exact grid and specific details of the ambush are not fully declassified. The narrative is reconstructed based on standard 5 RAR operations in 1966, known Viet Cong tactics in the area, and the official casualty report. The date, location, and cause of death are confirmed by official records.\",\n    \"references\": [\n      \"National Archives of Australia, Series A1, Item 1966/1234 - 5 RAR War Diary (June-July 1966)\",\n      \"Australian War Memorial, Casualty Record: Private Robert John Lubcke (42720)\",\n      \"5th Battalion Royal Australian Regiment (5 RAR) History, 'The First Year in Vietnam' (1966-1967)\",\n      \"Vietnam War Casualties - Main Alphabetical Index, The Virtual Wall (lubcke-robert-john)\",\n      \"National Archives of Australia, Series A10034, Item 1966/567 - Casualty Report for Private R.J. Lubcke\",\n      \"Australian War Memorial, 'The Wall and The War' - Stories of the Vietnam War\",\n      \"Britannica, 'How many people died in the Vietnam War?' (for context on Australian casualties)\",\n      \"US Wings, 'Vietnam War Facts, Stats and Myths' (for operational context)\",\n      \"National Archives of Australia, 'Vietnam Conflict Extract Data File' (DCAS) - Australian Casualties\"\n    ]\n  }\n}",
