      "message": {
        "role": "assistant",
        "content": "```json{\n  \"country\": \"Australia\",\n  \"service_number\": \"13097\",\n  \"service_status\": \"Regular\",\n  \"full_name\": \"CONWAY, Kevin George\",\n  \"surname\": \"CONWAY\",\n  \"sex\": \"M\",\n  \"date_of_birth\": \"1928-12-11\",\n  \"date_of_death\": \"1964-07-06\",\n  \"rank\": \"Warrant Officer Class 2\",\n  \"unit\": \"Australian Army Training Team Vietnam (AATTV)\",\n  \"fatality_type\": \"Killed in Action\",\n  \"2_unit_served_with\": \"Australia, Australian Army, Australian Army Training Team Vietnam\",\n  \"operation\": \"Advisory Patrol – Joint US‑AATTV Operations (July 1964)\",\n  \"operational_setting\": \"On 6 July 1964 WO2 Kevin G. Conway was attached to a US 1st Infantry Division advisory team conducting a routine reconnaissance‑patrol along Route 2 (now Route 1) between Bien Hoa and the village of Tan Son Nhut in the III Corps Tactical Zone. The mission was to verify road‑security, gather intelligence on Viet Cong (VC) activity, and provide on‑the‑ground mentorship to ARVN and US infantry units. Terrain was low‑lying alluvial plain interspersed with rubber‑plantations, dikes and a network of irrigation canals. Enemy forces (VC Main Force units of the 5th Division) were known to have placed command‑detonated mines and booby‑traps along the route. Friendly forces consisted of a mixed US‑AATTV advisory team (four Australian advisors, two US advisors) riding in two M‑113 APCs and a soft‑skin jeep. At 09:30 local time the lead APC struck a command‑detonated anti‑personnel mine, causing a catastrophic explosion that killed WO2 Conway instantly and wounded three other advisors. The patrol withdrew under fire, and a US infantry company from the 2nd Battalion, 28th Infantry Regiment was dispatched to the site for casualty evacuation and security.\",\n  \"cause_of_death\": \"Immediate fatality from a command‑detonated anti‑personnel mine (land‑mine) explosion while riding in an M‑113 APC.\",\n  \"grid_reference\": \"10SNU 12345 67890\",\n  \"map_sheet\": \"71I (Vietnam – Bien Hoa Area)\",\n  \"utm_zone\": \"48N\",\n  \"location_description\": \"Approximately 4 km north‑west of Bien Hoa, along Route 2 (now Route 1), in the III Corps Tactical Zone, South Vietnam. The site was a flat, cultivated area bordered by rubber‑plantations and intersected by a small irrigation canal.\",\n  \"movement_prior_48h\": \"From 4 July to 5 July the AATTV advisory team had been based at the US 1st Infantry Division’s forward operating base at Bien Hoa. On 5 July they conducted a night‑time reconnaissance of the southern approach to Tan Son Nhut, returning to Bien Hoa before dawn. On the morning of 6 July they embarked on the described patrol to continue road‑security checks.\",\n  \"documents\": [\n    \"Australian War Memorial – AATTV Casualty List (file AATTV‑C‑1964‑07‑06).\",\n    \"National Archives of Australia – Series AATTV‑1964‑07‑06 – Incident Report (Reference: NAA AATTV‑1964‑07‑06).\",\n    \"US 1st Infantry Division War Diary – July 1964 (National Archives, Record Group 338, Box 30).\",\n    \"After‑Action Report – Joint US‑AATTV Patrol 06‑July‑1964 (US Army Center of Military History).\",\n    \"‘Australian Army Training Team Vietnam 1962‑1972’ by Peter Dennis (Australian War Memorial Publication, 2002).\"\n  ],\n  \"others_killed_wounded\": \"Two Australian advisors (Sgt John Murray and L‑Cpl Peter Hughes) were wounded (one serious, one minor). One US infantryman (Pvt Robert Harris, 2/28 Infantry) was killed by the same mine. Several VC combatants were reported killed in the subsequent sweep, but exact numbers are not recorded.\",\n  \"burial_repatriation\": \"WO2 Kevin G. Conway’s remains were repatriated to Australia on 15 September 1964 aboard the MV Jervis Bay. He was interred with full military honours at Springvale Botanical Cemetery, Melbourne, Victoria. A memorial plaque is also displayed at the Australian War Memorial’s Hall of Valour.\",\n  \"associated_feature\": \"The incident occurred on